        <descriptionSet>
            <description extent="label text" href="http://www.asia.si.edu/collections/edan/object.php?q=fsg_S1997.26" pref="false" source="Arthur M. Sackler Gallery" dataDate="2015-11-30-19-03-00">
                <text dataDate="2015-11-30-19-03-00">Carved of dark gray limestone, this imposing Buddha head is characterized by a serene yet remote expression that is typical of early Tang dynasty religious images. Imperial patronage of Buddhism during the Tang dynasty, approximately seven hundred years after knowledge of Buddhism first reached China, resulted in the creation of some of the most impressive sculptures in Chinese history. For this Buddha head, all traces of Indian and Central Asian influence have been replaced by a native Chinese aesthetic. Sculptures of this style are found in the Longmen cave temples in Henan Province and may have been the source for this piece.</text>
                <author dataDate="2015-11-30-19-03-00">
